{"cursor":"2022","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox software\n| logo = name=Pe programming_language=C / C++ operating_system=BeOS like\n| genre=Text Editor license=MIT website=http://pe-editor.berlios.de/\n}}\n\n'Pe', short for Programmerâs Editor, is an open source text editor for the Be\nOperating System (BeOS). It is targeted towards source-code editing, and\nfeatures syntax highlighting for a large number of programming languages. It\nalso works as a basic source-level HTML editor, with some HTML autocompletion\nsupport, automatic updating of files included within other files, and direct FTP\nintegration. It is conceptually based on the Macintosh Programmer's Workshop and\nBBEdit, both of which are editing programs for the Mac OS.\n\nPe boasts features such as function autocompletion, powerful search-and-replace\noptions, and syntax highlighting for several programming languages. Pe was\nported to Mac OS X, Linux and Windows under the name Pepper, and the original\nBeOS code was open-sourced. It has been included in early builds of Haiku.\n\nPe was written by the Dutch programmer Maarten Hekkelman, who also wrote bdb,\nthe source-level debugger for the BeOS, and the spreadsheet Sum-It!, first for\nclassic Mac OS and later BeOS where it was packaged by Beatware as half of\nBeBasics; a lightweight office suite, which was also open-sourced.\n\nPe was used to write the BeOS Bible and possible other similar-era Scot Hacker\nworks, as well as In the Beginning... Was the Command Line by Neal Stephenson;\nboth of which works mention it.\n","linknr":165,"url":"Pe_(text_editor)","recorded":1375059402,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pe_(text_editor)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pe_(text_editor)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikip